To illustrate these results, we assume that the initial carbon stock is P0 = 826 GtC and the hazard rate is H(826) = 0.025 which increases to H(1652) = 0.067. So, as the stock of atmospheric carbon doubles and global warming increases by 3 °C (using a climate sensitivity of 3), the average time it takes for the tip to occur drops from 40 to 15 years. The within-year risks of a catastrophe are thus 2.5% to start off with and rise by 4.2% once temperature has risen by 3 °C. Suppose that at the end of the next half century the temperature is 3 °C higher and that the hazard rate rises linearly. Using the expression for the cumulative hazard in Sect. 2, below Eq. (1), we can show that the cumulative risk of a catastrophe occurring during this half century is 91%: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
